{{Infobox company | name = Auspex Systems | logo = | type = | industry = [[Computer data storage]] | fate = | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = 1987 | founder = Larry Boucher | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = [[Santa Clara, California]] | hq_location_country = | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = [[Network-attached storage]] devices | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''Auspex Systems''' was a [[computer data storage]] company founded in 1987 by Larry Boucher, who was previously CEO of [[Adaptec]]. It was headquartered in [[Santa Clara, California]].
Auspex introduced the first [[network-attached storage]] (NAS) devices. After an [[initial public offering]] in 1993, shares were traded on the [[NASDAQ]] exchange under symbol ASPX.<ref name="K1997" /> One of the unique features of their systems was the ease with which volumes could be transparently mirrored and migrated between physical disks. Auspex systems used Functional Multiprocessing, essentially [[Asymmetric multiprocessing]], that allowed the systems to scale functions independently -- such as networking, file processing, or storage processing. There was a Host Processor running Unix that controlled the whole system. This 'system within a system' could even be rebooted without interrupting file servicing! They became a leading provider of [[data center]] storage in the mid-1990s but fell behind [[NetApp]] in the field.<ref>{{Cite web |title= After losing market share to NTAP and EMC, Auspex is back with a new management team and new NAS products |date= August 15, 2001 |work= Network Computing |url= http://www.networkcomputing.com/storage/auspex/1812823803 |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref> Early cabinet rack models held sets of 3-4gb disks the size of small shoeboxes.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} Bruce N. Moore joined in 1995 as president and chief executive officer.<ref name="K1997">{{Cite web |title= Form 10-K: Annual Report for the Period Ending June 30, 1997 |publisher= United States Securities and Exchange Commission |date= September 26, 1997 |url= https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/860749/0000891618-97-003915.txt |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref> Boucher left the company in 1997 to found [[Alacritech]].<ref>{{Cite web |title= Larry Boucher |publisher= Computer History Museum |url= http://www.computerhistory.org/events/bio/Larry,Boucher |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref>
Their 4Front or NS2000 model, initially offered in 1999 as a stackable system, held drawers of disks and was plagued by Mylex RAID controller issues which contributed to their bankruptcy in June 2003. Their last product, the NSc3000, was the first multi-vendor SAN-NAS gateway and essentially kept the same NAS front-end but could connect via [[Fibre Channel]] to any SAN disk array.{{citation needed |date=September 2016}} After the burst of the [[dot-com bubble]], in February, 2000, the company worked with Regent Pacific to select Gary J. Sbona as interim chief executive.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Auspex Systems Announces New Chairman of the Board and Interim Chief Executive Officer |date= February 15, 2000 |work= Press release |url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/auspex-systems-announces-new-chairman-of-the-board-and-interim-chief-executive-officer-72608562.html |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref> When the company was liquidated in 2003, its [[patent portfolio]] was acquired by NetApp<ref>{{Cite web |title= Network Appliance Acquires Auspex Patent Portfolio |date= June 18, 2003 |work= Press release |publisher= Network Appliance, Inc. |url= http://www.netapp.com/us/company/news/press-releases/network_appliance_acquires_auspex_patent_portfolio.aspx |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref> and its services business went to GlassHouse Technologies for about $280,000.<ref>{{Cite web |title= GlassHouse Picks Auspex's Bones |date= June 16, 2003 |work= Network Computing |url= http://www.networkcomputing.com/careers/glasshouse-picks-auspexs-bones/1963783552 |accessdate= September 16, 2016 }}</ref>
